<DOC><DOCNO> AP881221-0217 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0128EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-21 0538</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0565</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Inflation slowed to an annual rate of 3 percentlast month and economic growth did the same in the third quarter,the government says.   The Labor Department report released Tuesday eased fears amongmany economists and market watchers that an overheating economy wasabout to trigger a wage-price spiral.   Seasonally-adjusted consumer prices rose just 0.25 percent inNovember compared with a 0.4 percent increase in October, the LaborDepartment said. Before the seasonal adjustments, prices rose only0.1 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The economy expanded at a moderate 2.5 percentpace during the July-September quarter, the government reported, butanalysts said growth was rebounding and the Federal Reserve probablywould nudge interest rates higher as a result.   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that growth of the grossnational product, the broadest measure of economic health, slowedduring the third quarter from 3.0 percent in the second quarter.   The GNP, after adjusting for inflation, rose $24.2 billion to anannual rate of $4.01 trillion in the third quarter.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Labor Department's encouraging report oninflation added a spark of life to some financial markets and easedconcerns about higher interest rates, but most analysts remainedwary about the economy's direction.   The dollar rallied Tuesday against most major currencies inforeign-exchange trading in the United States and abroad, while bondprices headed sharply higher.   But on Wall Street, stocks declined. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials closed 6.61 points lower at 2,166.07.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President-elect Bush, emphasizing hisopposition to tax increases, appointed Republican Paul Laxalt andDemocrat Thomas Ashley to a national commission struggling to find aformula for reducing the federal budget deficit.   ``I intend to hold the line on taxes,'' Bush said Tuesday.``There are a lot of people around saying I can't do that.''   The appointments put the National Economic Commission at its fullstrength of 14 people. The panel was created last year afterOctober's stock market crash.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Zenith Electronics Corp. hopes to break newground in the fight against unfairly low-priced imports by askingthe government to monitor imports of televisions from 10 countries,Zenith's chairman says.   The comments Tuesday by Jerry Pearlman in a wide-rangingtelephone interview were the first public disclosure of a keycomponent in Zenith's plan for returning to consistent profitability.   In another development related to foreign dumping, AmericanTelephone andamp; Telegraph Co. said it would file a petition with theU.S. government alleging that manufacturers in Japan, Taiwan andSouth Korea are charging unfairly low prices for small-businessphone gear in the United States.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Corporations reported a 3.9 percent rise inafter-tax profits for the third quarter, down from an 8.9 percentsurge in the previous quarter but substantially above thepreliminary estimate last month, the government says.   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that profits rose $6.4billion to a seasonally-adjusted annual level of $169.1 billion forthe third quarter.   That compares with the slight 0.2 percent rise reported a monthago, but the department noted almost all of the improvement camefrom profits earned by foreign subsidiaries of U.S. companies.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>